  note = {Self-published monograph via St. Martin's Press; not peer-reviewed. Book title is "The Grammar of Consciousness," not "The Grammar of Reality" — a parallel agent research pass conflated these, illustrating genealogical collapse.},
  abstract = {Moss's book uses "grammar" in the structural sense to characterize the organization of consciousness, arguing that consciousness has a basic structure (or grammar) which language reflects and through which human experience takes on its particular character. Drawing on Michael Polanyi's theory of tacit knowing, Moss develops a model of how the particulars of consciousness are integrated into comprehensive entities through grammatical processes. The book includes a chapter titled "Knowing and Reality" that explores the relationship between consciousness and reality. NOTE: This book is titled "The Grammar of Consciousness," not "The Grammar of Reality" --- a distinction that a parallel agent research pass conflated, illustrating the very failure class (genealogical collapse) that the pass identified.},
  annotation = {For HUMMBL, Moss's work is relevant as an example of the grammar metaphor applied to consciousness rather than reality directly, demonstrating the range of domains to which the grammar metaphor has been extended: science (Pearson), experience (Kant, Thalos), meaning (Wittgenstein), being (Heidegger), process (Whitehead, Bohm), consciousness (Moss), and organization (Cabrera). The book's Polanyian framework also connects the grammar metaphor to tacit knowing, a dimension absent from the other sources.},
