  year      = {1887},
  publisher = {Vintage Books},
  address   = {New York},
  doi-unavailable = {19th century publication; no DOI for original. Vintage edition ISBN provided.},
  isbn      = {9780679724629},
  abstract  = {Nietzsche's Genealogy traces the historical origins of moral concepts, arguing that what we call morality is the product of power struggles rather than divine or rational foundations. The three essays examine: (1) the transformation of "good" (originally meaning noble) and "bad" (originally meaning common) into "good" (meaning selfless) and "evil" (meaning powerful), (2) the origin of guilt in the creditor-debtor relationship, and (3) the ascetic ideal -- the valorization of self-denial as a response to the meaninglessness of existence. Nietzsche's method is genealogical: rather than asking what morality means, he asks how it came to mean what it does. For HUMMBL, the genealogical method is a powerful IN (Inversion) tool: instead of analyzing what a concept means, invert it to ask how it acquired its meaning. The power-morality connection provides a framework for examining how AI governance norms are products of power relations rather than neutral principles.},
